25|$|The {{evolutionary}} {{progression from}} simple, undifferentiated homogeneity to complex, differentiated heterogeneity was exemplified, Spencer argued, {{by the development}} of society. He developed a theory of two types of society, the militant and the industrial, which corresponded to this evolutionary progression. Militant society, structured around relationships of hierarchy and obedience, was simple and undifferentiated; <b>industrial</b> <b>society,</b> based on voluntary, contractually assumed social obligations, was complex and differentiated. Society, which Spencer conceptualised as a 'social organism' evolved from the simpler state to the more complex according to the universal law of evolution. Moreover, <b>industrial</b> <b>society</b> was the direct descendant of the ideal society developed in Social Statics, although Spencer now equivocated over whether the evolution of society would result in anarchism (as he had first believed) or whether it pointed to a continued role for the state, albeit one reduced to the minimal functions of the enforcement of contracts and external defence.|$|E
